 :tx/provenance :observed
 :tx/rationale "THE 10/10 STORAGE ARCHITECTURE — inspired by asupersync + database WAL patterns: CURRENT: 13K+ individual .edn files, one per transaction. list_tx_hashes does readdir over 256 shard dirs. Every flush/guard checks the full directory. File-per-txn is O(1) write but O(F) enumerate. At 100K transactions: enumerate = 100ms. At 1M: seconds. PROPOSED: Write-Ahead Log (WAL) architecture. Three tiers: (1) WAL file (.braid/wal.bin): append-only binary log. Each entry = length-prefix + bincode(TxFile) + CRC32. Append is O(1) with O_APPEND (kernel-atomic for writes < PIPE_BUF=4096 bytes on Linux; larger writes use flock on the WAL). Enumerate = read sequential file, not readdir. (2) Checkpoint file (.braid/checkpoint.bin): periodic full store snapshot. Created by daemon on shutdown or at interval. (3) Recovery: load checkpoint + replay WAL entries after checkpoint LSN. PROPERTIES: (a) Append-only (C1) — WAL entries are never modified, only appended. CRC32 detects corruption. (b) Content-addressed (C2) — each WAL entry contains the TxFile with BLAKE3-hashed datoms. (c) O(1) write — append to WAL is a single write() syscall. (d) O(1) membership check — daemon tracks seen TxIds in a HashSet. No directory listing needed. (e) Concurrent-safe — O_APPEND is atomic for small writes; flock for large ones. No stale cache possible because there IS no cache file to get stale — the WAL IS the durable log and the daemon IS the live index. (f) CRDT merge — two WAL files can be concatenated (set union of entries, deduplicated by content hash). WHY THIS IS 10/10: Eliminates the root cause of EVERY performance and correctness issue we diagnosed: no store.bin cache (daemon is the live index), no directory listing (WAL is sequential), no overlapping LiveStores (daemon + WAL), no stale fingerprint (no fingerprint needed). The .edn per-txn files become a COMPATIBILITY layer for git tracking, not the primary storage path."
